The '''Museum David and Alice van Buuren''' is a private house built from 1924 to 1928 for banker and art collector David van Buuren and his wife Alice in [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]. The house was decorated by David and Alice as a ''[[Gesamtkunstwerk|total work of art]]'' to present their art collection in a rich [[Art Deco]] interior. The house is surrounded by gardens designed by [[Jules Buyssens]] in 1925 and [[Ren<U+00E9> Pech<U+00E8>re]] in 1968 and 1970. The house was declared a National Heritage site in 2001.{{sfn|Minist<U+00E8>re de la R<U+00E9>gion de Bruxelles-Capitale|2001|p=3}} The private house became a museum in 1975 according to the testament of Alice van Buuren.

==History==
David van Buuren (1886-1955) was born into a Jewish family in [[Gouda]], [[Netherlands]].{{sfn|Swimberghe|2001|p=115}} He settled in Brussels in 1909 to become an important private banker. He married the Belgian Alice Piette (1890-1973) in 1922. From 1924-1928 the van Buurens commissioned the Belgian architects [[L<U+00E9>on Emmanuel Govaerts|L<U+00E9>on Govaerts]] and [[Alexis Van Vaerenbergh]] to built their  house on the L<U+00E9>o Errera Avenue in [[Uccle]].{{sfn|Minist<U+00E8>re de la R<U+00E9>gion de Bruxelles-Capitale|2001|p=7}}<ref name="Carez1996">{{harvnb|Carez|1996|p=24}}</ref> The  outdoor architecture is  typical of the [[Amsterdam School]], while its [[Art Deco]] interior was decorated by Belgian, French and Dutch designers with rare furniture, carpets and stained-glass windows.

From 1928 to 1970 the van Buurens hosted people such as [[Raoul Dufy]], [[Jacques Pr<U+00E9>vert]], [[Ren<U+00E9> Lalique]], [[Sergei Diaghilev]], [[Erik Satie]], [[Ren<U+00E9> Magritte]], [[David Ben-Gurion ]]. The private house became a museum in 1975 according to the testament of Alice van Buuren.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.museumvanbuuren.be/en/maison.php |title=House |first= |last=  |work=Official website van Buuren Museum |year=2013 [last update] |accessdate=19 August 2013}}</ref>

==Collections==
[[File:Fall of Icarus - Brueghel -Museum van Buuren.jpg|thumb|right|''"[[Landscape with the Fall of Icarus]]"'', ca. 1590-95, oil  on wood ({{convert|63|x|90|cm}}), Circle of P.Bruegel the Elder, Museum van Buuren, Brussels, Belgium.]]
David van Buuren decorated his house with paintings from  [[James Ensor]], [[Joachim Patinir]], [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder]], [[Hercules Seghers]], [[Pieter Jansz Saenredam]], [[Tsuguharu Foujita]], [[Kees van Dongen]], [[Vincent van Gogh]], [[Henri  Fantin-Latour]], [[Rik Wouters]], [[Gustave De Smet]], [[Xavier Mellery]] en [[Constant Permeke]]. David was the [[patron]] of Belgian [[expressionism|expressionist]] painter [[Gustave van de Woestijne]]. Van Buurens collections consists of 32 paintings of Van de Woestijne.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.museumvanbuuren.be/en/oeuvres.php |title=Collection|first= |last= |work=Official website van Buuren Museum |year=2013 [last update] |accessdate=19 August 2013}}</ref>

The living room is decorated with a rich collections of  modernist carpets designed by the Dutch designer [[Jaap Gidding ]]{{sfn|Day|2002}} and a grand piano made of rosewood designed by [[Julius Bl<U+00FC>thner]].{{sfn|Conseil de la Musique de la Communaut<U+00E9> Fran<U+00E7>aise de Belgique|1992|p=169-170}} [[Jan Eisenloeffel]] designed the {{convert|500|kg|abbr=on}} Art Deco chandelier in the entrance hall.{{sfn|Minist<U+00E8>re de la R<U+00E9>gion de Bruxelles-Capitale|2001|p=4}}{{sfn|Swimberghe|2001|p=115}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Aus liebe zu den k<U+00FC>nsten|url=http://www.deimel-wittmar.de/files/ad/AD_05_08_van_Buuren_Br%C3%BCssel.pdf|journal=Architectural Digest|date=May 2008|language=German}}</ref>

On 16 July 2013, the paintings ''"Shrimps and Shells"'' of Belgian painter James Ensor and ''"The Thinker"'' by Dutch artist Kees Van Dongen and eight small works by old masters were stolen.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.artmediaagency.com/en/70379/ten-paintings-stolen-in-belgium/ |title=Ten paintings stolen in Belgium   |author=Art Media Agency |work=artmediaagency.com |date=23 July 2013 |accessdate=21 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://newsoftheartworld.com/lightning-raid-on-the-van-buuren-museum/?lang=en |title=Lightning raid on the van Buuren museum |author=NEWS OF THE ART WORLD|work=newsoftheartworld.com |date=23 July 2013  |accessdate=21 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lemonde.fr/culture/article/2013/07/16/vol-dans-un-musee-de-bruxelles_3448620_3246.html |title=Vol dans un mus<U+00E9>e de Bruxelles |first= |last=  |work=[[Le Monde]] |date=16 July 2013|accessdate=21 August 2013|language=French}}</ref>
==Garden==
The {{convert|1.2|ha|adj=on|abbr=on}} garden is divided in three parts: the ''"Picturesque Garden"'' designed by [[Jules Buyssens]] in 1925, the ''"Labyrinth"'', inspired by the [[Song of Songs]] and decorated with seven sculptures by the Belgian sculptor [[Andr<U+00E9> Willequet]] and the ''"Garden of the Hearts"'' designed by Belgian landscape designer [[Ren<U+00E9> Pech<U+00E8>re]] in 1968 and 1970 respectively.<ref>{{harvnb|Taylor|2006|p=42}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Pech<U+00E8>re|1987|p=}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Pech<U+00E8>re|2008|p=192}}</ref>

